# {{PLUGIN_NAME}}

EdgeBase plugin for {{PLUGIN_DESCRIPTION}}.

## Installation

```bash
npm install {{PLUGIN_NAME}}                         # server plugin
npm install {{PLUGIN_NAME}}-client @edge-base/web  # optional typed web client
```

## Configuration

Add the plugin to your `edgebase.config.ts`:

```typescript
import { {{PLUGIN_NAME_CAMEL}}Plugin } from '{{PLUGIN_NAME}}';

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [
    {{PLUGIN_NAME_CAMEL}}Plugin({
      apiKey: process.env.MY_PLUGIN_API_KEY!,
    }),
  ],
});
```

## Usage

### Client SDK

```typescript
import { createClient } from '@edge-base/web';
import { createPlugin } from '{{PLUGIN_NAME}}-client';

const client = createClient('https://my-app.edgebase.fun');
const plugin = createPlugin(client);

// Call plugin functions — fully typed
const result = await plugin.doSomething({ input: 'hello' });

// Read plugin tables
const items = await plugin.getItems();
```

### Server Functions

```typescript
// Inside another server function — inter-function calls
const result = await ctx.admin.functions.call('{{PLUGIN_NAME}}/hello', {
  input: 'hello',
});
```

### Access Rules

Tables use EdgeBase access rules. Common patterns:

```typescript
access: {
  read: (auth, row) => auth?.id === row.userId,   // Owner only
  insert: (auth) => auth !== null,                // Any authenticated user
  update: (auth, row) => auth?.id === row.userId, // Owner only
  delete: () => false,                            // Nobody
}
```

### Plugin Manifest

Put CLI-facing metadata directly in `definePlugin()`:

```typescript
manifest: {
  description: 'Short description shown by edgebase plugins list',
  docsUrl: 'https://example.com/docs/{{PLUGIN_NAME}}',
  configTemplate: {
    apiKey: 'CHANGE_ME',
  },
}
```

## Development

```bash
cd server && npm run dev   # Watch mode (auto-rebuild on changes)
npx edgebase dev           # Start local dev server
```

